#   DOG-002: relocate the diff core (`BRAM`+`NEIL`) from `graf/` into `dog/`

`dog/WEAVE` ([DOG-001]) must sit in the `dog/` layer, below the verb dogs, but the weave diff core it needs — `graf/BRAM` (banded Myers) and `graf/NEIL` (edit-list canonicalize/cleanup/shift) — lives in `graf/`, ABOVE `dog/`. Move both down to `dog/` (or `abc/` if fully generic) WITHOUT behaviour change, so `dog/WEAVE` has no upward dependency. Pure relocation; the rewrite itself is [DOG-003].

##  Input

### Context
 -  `graf/WEAVE.c` includes `graf/BRAM.h` + `graf/NEIL.h`; `WEAVEDiff`/`Apply`
    call `BRAMu64s` and `NEILCanon`/`Cleanup`/`Shift`.
 -  `BRAM`/`NEIL` are generic edit-list machinery over `abc/DIFF` gauges with
    no keeper/graf-state dependency — candidates for `dog/` or `abc/`.
 -  `dog/INDEX.md` defines dog as "between abc and the verb dogs"; a
    graf→dog include would invert that layering.

### Goals
 -  `BRAM`+`NEIL` headers/impl live at `dog/` (or `abc/`), behaviour
    byte-identical; graf keeps compiling via the new include path.
 -  No call-site logic change; `graf blame`/`diff`/`merge` output unchanged
    (`GRAFblameident` byte-for-byte).

### Constraints
 -  If a unit pulls graf/keeper state, SPLIT it rather than dragging a
    dependency down; verify includes are abc-only first.
 -  No `abc/` surface change without review; prefer `dog/` when uncertain.

##  WIP

### Design decisions
 -  Target `dog/` (peer of `dog/HUNK`); choose `abc/` only if includes are
    100% abc. Move the matching tests too (`graf/test/{BRAM,NEIL}*`).
 -  Update `CMakeLists.txt`, `graf/INDEX.md`, `dog/INDEX.md` in the same land;
    rewrite include paths repo-wide via spot.

### TODOs
-[ ] Confirm BRAM/NEIL include sets are abc-only (no graf/keeper symbols).
-[ ] Move headers+impl+tests to `dog/`; fix include paths repo-wide (spot).
-[ ] ctest green; `graf blame/diff/merge` byte-identical to pre-move.

### Blockers and bummers
 -  None expected; pure relocation. A hidden graf dep becomes its own ticket
    and a unit split, never a layer inversion.

